However, the majority of inhibitors have low electronegativity (
                           χ
                        ) values, which indicate their capacity to offer electrons to a metal surface. High electronegativity values, on the other hand, imply that the inhibitor molecule has a great ability to attract and absorb electrons from metal surface atoms (i.e., back-donation), allowing it to create a stronger connection with metal atoms. The electronegativity of the investigated molecule is low, demonstrating exceptional electron donation ability to the steel surface, according to the computed results shown in Table 3. In addition, hardness (η) and softness (σ) values can be used to determine a compound's stability, i.e., soft compounds have better protection than hard compounds due to the integrity created by the smooth coating of electrons on the steel surface during adsorption, indicating effective protection. The Ce-MOF tend to have lower values of hardness (η) and absolute softness (σ), indicating a strong ability to facilitate electron donation to the steel, resulting in a strong anticorrosion ability. Fig. 9 demonstrates that the most negative regions are generally surrounded in N atoms, nevertheless in the examined compounds; high electron density can be seen over the Ce-atoms and five-member ring complex. The ideal places for interactions, anchoring and formation of a protective coating are these positions with high electron density as found in the studied molecule. Additionally, when ΔN > 0, an electron transfers from the Ce-MOF to the metal surface. Also, the inhibitor's ability to donate an electron would be improved when ΔN values are < 3.6. As evidence, the obtained ΔN value has a (+ve) sign and low compared to 3.6 range, thus, explaining the capability of the Ce-MOF to donate electrons to the metal.
